What is Web Scraping?
We were originally going to learn to scrape Facebook today.
However, Facebook’s recent changes to their API—changes
motivated by recent data access concerns at the company—have
made this diﬃcult.
Since we don’t have much time, we’re going to focus instead on
scraping The New York Times.
We’ll end with a brief example of how to build a custom scraper. It’s
much more labor-intensive, but some of you may want to use it to get
data for your ﬁnal papers.

NYT API
NYT has several diﬀerent APIs you can use to scrape data.
These include APIs for scraping news articles, book reviews/book
bestseller lists, most popular articles, user comments, geocoded
data, and movie reviews, among others.
We’re going to focus on the article search API today.
The R package we’re going to use is called rtimes (Chamberlain
2017).
A lot of the code used here is from/adapted from Chamberlain (n.d.)

Authentication
The authentication process is similar to the one for rtweet.
Go to developer.nytimes.com and click “Sign In.” Create a NYT
Developers account.
Once you have signed into your account, click the arrow next to your
e-mail address in the top corner. Then click on “My Apps.” Click “+ New
App.”
Give the app a name and description. Mark that you are using the Article
Search API. Click “create.”
Copy the key under the “API Keys” section.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 January 25, 2019 7 / 43
Now just plug in your API key below and run that line:
# Au th ent ica te yo ur self
Sys . setenv ( NYTIMES _ AS _KEY = " api _ key _ here ")
And we’re ready!

Coverage of “Unite the Right” Rally
Let’s gather some data on NYT ’s coverage of the “Unite the Right”
protests in Charlottesville, VA, in late 2017.
The event took place from August 11
th
to August 12
th
, 2017, and was a
response to the removal of Confederate statues.
The Charlottesville location was motivated by an earlier May protest
organized by Richard Spencer.
The rally culminated in a neo-Nazi driving his car into a crowd of
counter-protestors, killing one.
The events—and political conversations around the events—carried a lot
of media coverage.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 January 25, 2019 10 / 43
Let’s collect all NYT articles published from the date of Spencer’s ﬁrst
rally—May 13, 2017—to the end of that year. Here’s how we’ll do it:
# Scr ape some NYT ar ti cl e dat a
ny . articles <- as _ search (q = ’" Unite the Right "’,
begin _ date = " 20170513 " , end _ date = " 20 171231 " ,
all _ results = T , sleep = 10)
ny article . data <- ny . articles $ data
The all results option indicates that we want all articles that use the
exact phrase “unite the right” somewhere in the article, and the sleep
option tells the scraper to “pause” the program so that you don’t exceed
the rate limits set by the API (this prevents the scraper from aborting).

Building a Web Scraper
“Out-of-the-box” scrapers like rtweet and rtimes are great, but
sometimes you will need to build your own web scraper.
For instance, maybe you want to scrape data from a site that doesn’t have
a pre-built scraper.
Admittedly, building a web scraper has a more pronounced learning curve.
But for those of you interested in scraping from a more esoteric site or a
site that otherwise doesn’t have a convenient R scraper ready to go, this is
what you’ll need to do.
The code gets a bit complicated right here, so don’t feel like you have to
follow along on your computer.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 January 25, 2019 23 / 43

Building a Web Scraper
A popular R package for customizing web scrapers is
rvest (Wickham 2016).
It’s used to create and parse HTML ﬁles from a URL,
identify and extract the relevant HTML nodes, and
convert them into a data frame.
You identify the HTML nodes using CSS (Cascading
Style Sheets) selectors or XPath code. We’ll focus on
using CSS selectors.
Instructor: Marshall A. Taylor SOC/MDSC 43919 January 25, 2019 26 / 43
Using CSS Selectors
So how do we ﬁnd the relevant HTML nodes in the reviews? Say, the
nodes identifying the authors, titles, ratings, review texts, and so on?
We’ll extract them by ﬁnding the relevant CSS selectors. Speciﬁcally, we’ll
use SelectorGadget—an interactive program that helps you identify the
relevant CSS selectors.
Be sure to watch the video at the linked site above to see SelectorGadget
in action. Wickham also gives a good rundown on using SelectorGadget
with rvest.
SelectorGadget has a convenient Google Chrome extension. Once it’s
installed, you’ll see it in your bookmark bar:
Figure 7: SelectorGadget in the Chrome Bookmark Bar

Wrapping Up
Web scraping can range from fairly easy to very complicated.
It depends on a range of factors. Is there a nice out-of-the-box scraper
that handles a lot of the API wrangling for you (such as rtweet and
rtimes)? How much data do you want to scrape? Does the API have
strict rate limits? If you’re using CSS selectors, how “messy” is the site?
Many of the datasets we will use in this class are courtesy of web
scrapers—but not all of them.
I do not expect you to build your own custom scrapers with rvest. But if
you want to explore this option in your lab assignments or ﬁnal papers, let
me know!
